# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: terrain-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] In computer graphics, **clipmapping** is a method of clipping a mipmap to a subset of data pertinent to the geometry being displayed.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] The technique was introduced by Christopher C.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] Jones as a "virtual mipmap" for caching arbitrarily large textures in finite physical memory for real-time rendering.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] This is useful for loading as little data as possible when memory is limited, such as on a graphics processing unit.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] For terrain rendering, the idea was adapted into geometry clipmaps, which use nested regular grids centered on the viewer and update them incrementally as the viewpoint moves.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] The technique is used for LODing in NVIDIA’s implementation of voxel cone tracing.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] The high-resolution levels of the mipmapped scene representation are clipped to a region near the camera, while lower resolution levels are clipped further away.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] MegaTexture is a clipmap implementation developed by id Software.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] It was introduced in their id Tech 4 engine and also appeared in id Tech 5 and id Tech 6 before being removed in id Tech 7.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] MegaTexture is a texture allocation technique that uses a single, extremely large texture rather than repeating multiple smaller textures.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] It is also featured in Splash Damage's game *Enemy Territory: Quake Wars*, and was developed by id Software former technical director John Carmack.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] MegaTexture employs a single large texture space for static terrain.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] The texture is stored on removable media or a computer's hard drive and streamed as needed, allowing large amounts of detail and variation over a large area with comparatively little RAM usage.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] Depending on the pixel resolution per square meter, covering a large area could require several gigabytes of memory.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] However, RAM is also filled by the rest of the game and the underlying operating system, limiting the amount available for texturing.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] As the player moves around the game, different sections of the MegaTexture are loaded into memory.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] They are then scaled to the correct size and applied to the 3D models of the terrain.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] Id has presented a more advanced technique that builds upon the MegaTexture idea and virtualizes both the geometry and the textures to obtain unique geometry down to the equivalent of the texel: the sparse voxel octree (SVO).
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] It works by raycasting the geometry represented by voxels (instead of triangles) stored in an octree.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] The geometric detail that can be obtained using this method is nearly infinite, which removes the need for faking 3-dimensional details with techniques such as normal mapping.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] Despite that most voxel rendering tests use very large amounts of memory (up to several GB), Jon Olick of id Software claimed the technology is able to compress such SVO to 1.15 bits per voxel of position data.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] Unlike clipmaps, which clip each mip level around a viewpoint-dependent clipcenter and therefore work best for terrain, virtual texturing preprocesses texture data into equally sized tiles that can be streamed for arbitrary textured geometry.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] *Rage*, powered by the id Tech 5 engine, uses a more advanced technique called virtual texturing.
[src:terrain-rendering/clipmap] Textures can measure up to 128000×128000 pixels and are also used for in-game models and sprites, etc. and not just the terrain.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] A **digital elevation model** (**DEM**) or **digital surface model** (**DSM**) is a 3D computer graphics representation of elevation data to represent terrain or overlaying objects, commonly of a planet, moon, or asteroid.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] A "global DEM" refers to a discrete global grid.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] DEMs are used often in geographic information systems (GIS), and are the most common basis for digitally produced relief maps.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] A **digital terrain model** (**DTM**) represents specifically the ground surface while DEM and DSM may represent tree top canopy or building roofs.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] While a DSM may be useful for landscape modeling, city modeling and visualization applications, a DTM is often required for flood or drainage modeling, land-use studies, geological applications, and other applications, and in planetary science.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] There is no universal usage of the terms *digital elevation model* (DEM), *digital terrain model* (DTM) and *digital surface model* (DSM) in scientific literature.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] In most cases the term *digital surface model* represents the earth's surface and includes all objects on it.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] In contrast to a DSM, the *digital terrain model* (DTM) represents the bare ground surface without any objects like plants and buildings (see the figure on the right).
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] DEM is often used as a generic term for DSMs and DTMs, only representing height information without any further definition about the surface.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Other definitions equalise the terms DEM and DTM, equalise the terms DEM and DSM, define the DEM as a subset of the DTM, which also represents other morphological elements, or define a DEM as a rectangular grid and a DTM as a three-dimensional model (TIN).
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Most of the data providers (USGS, ERSDAC, CGIAR, Spot Image) use the term DEM as a generic term for DSMs and DTMs.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Some datasets such as SRTM or the ASTER GDEM are originally DSMs, although in forested areas, SRTM reaches into the tree canopy giving readings somewhere between a DSM and a DTM).
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] DTMs are created from high resolution DSM datasets using complex algorithms to filter out buildings and other objects, a process known as "bare-earth extraction".
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] In the following, the term DEM is used as a generic term for DSMs and DTMs.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] A DEM can be represented as a raster (a grid of squares, also known as a heightmap when representing elevation) or as a vector-based triangular irregular network (TIN).
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] The TIN DEM dataset is also referred to as a primary (measured) DEM, whereas the Raster DEM is referred to as a secondary (computed) DEM.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] The DEM could be acquired through techniques such as photogrammetry, lidar, IfSAR or InSAR, land surveying, etc.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] DEMs are commonly built using data collected using remote sensing techniques, but they may also be built from land surveying.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] The digital elevation model itself consists of a matrix of numbers, but the data from a DEM is often rendered in visual form to make it understandable to humans.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] This visualization may be in the form of a contoured topographic map, or could use shading and false color assignment (or "pseudo-color") to render elevations as colors (for example, using green for the lowest elevations, shading to red, with white for the highest elevation.).
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Visualizations are sometimes also done as oblique views, reconstructing a synthetic visual image of the terrain as it would appear looking down at an angle.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] In these oblique visualizations, elevations are sometimes scaled using "vertical exaggeration" in order to make subtle elevation differences more noticeable.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Some scientists, however, object to vertical exaggeration as misleading the viewer about the true landscape.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Mappers may prepare digital elevation models in a number of ways, but they frequently use remote sensing rather than direct survey data.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Older methods of generating DEMs often involve interpolating digital contour maps that may have been produced by direct survey of the land surface.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] This method is still used in mountain areas, where interferometry is not always satisfactory.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Note that contour line data or any other sampled elevation datasets (by GPS or ground survey) are not DEMs, but may be considered digital terrain models.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] A DEM implies that elevation is available continuously at each location in the study area.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Other kinds of stereoscopic pairs can be employed using the digital image correlation method, where two optical images are acquired with different angles taken from the same pass of an airplane or an Earth Observation Satellite (such as the HRS instrument of SPOT5 or the VNIR band of ASTER).
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] The SPOT 1 satellite (1986) provided the first usable elevation data for a sizeable portion of the planet's landmass, using two-pass stereoscopic correlation.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] The HRS instrument on SPOT 5 has acquired over 100 million square kilometers of stereo pairs.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] A tool of increasing value in planetary science has been use of orbital altimetry used to make digital elevation map of planets.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] A primary tool for this is laser altimetry but radar altimetry is also used.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Planetary digital elevation maps made using laser altimetry include the Mars Orbiter Laser Altimeter (MOLA) mapping of Mars, the Lunar Orbital Laser Altimeter (LOLA) and Lunar Altimeter (LALT) mapping of the Moon, and the Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA) mapping of Mercury.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] In planetary mapping, each planetary body has a unique reference surface.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] New Horizons' Long Range Reconnaissance Imager used stereo photogrammetry to produce partial surface elevation maps of Pluto and 486958 Arrokoth.
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] The quality of a DEM is a measure of how accurate elevation is at each pixel (absolute accuracy) and how accurately is the morphology presented (relative accuracy).
[src:terrain-rendering/digital-elevation-model] Quality assessment of DEM can be performed by comparison of DEMs from different sources.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] For years, displacement mapping was a peculiarity of high-end rendering systems like PhotoRealistic RenderMan, while realtime APIs, like OpenGL and DirectX, were only starting to use this feature.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] One of the reasons for this is that the original implementation of displacement mapping required an adaptive tessellation of the surface in order to obtain enough micropolygons whose size matched the size of a pixel on the screen.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Displacement mapping includes the term mapping which refers to a texture map being used to modulate the displacement strength.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] The displacement direction is usually the local surface normal.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Today, many renderers allow programmable shading which can create high quality (multidimensional) procedural textures and patterns at arbitrarily high frequencies.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] The use of the term mapping becomes arguable then, as no texture map is involved anymore.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Therefore, the broader term **displacement** is often used today to refer to a super concept that also includes displacement based on a texture map.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Renderers using the REYES algorithm, or similar approaches based on micropolygons, have allowed displacement mapping at arbitrary high frequencies since they became available almost 20 years ago.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] The first commercially available renderer to implement a micropolygon displacement mapping approach through REYES was Pixar's PhotoRealistic RenderMan.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Micropolygon renderers commonly tessellate geometry themselves at a granularity suitable for the image being rendered.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] That is: the modeling application delivers high-level primitives to the renderer.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Examples include true NURBS- or subdivision surfaces.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] The renderer then tessellates this geometry into micropolygons at render time using view-based constraints derived from the image being rendered.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Other renderers that require the modeling application to deliver objects pre-tessellated into arbitrary polygons or even triangles have defined the term displacement mapping as moving the vertices of these polygons.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Often the displacement direction is also limited to the surface normal at the vertex.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] While conceptually similar, those polygons are usually a lot larger than micropolygons.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] The quality achieved from this approach is thus limited by the geometry's tessellation density a long time before the renderer gets access to it.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] This difference between displacement mapping in micropolygon renderers vs. displacement mapping in a non-tessellating (macro)polygon renderers can often lead to confusion in conversations between people whose exposure to each technology or implementation is limited.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Even more so, as in recent years, many non-micropolygon renderers have added the ability to do displacement mapping of a quality similar to that which a micropolygon renderer is able to deliver naturally.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] To distinguish between the crude pre-tessellation-based displacement these renderers did before, the term **sub-pixel displacement** was introduced to describe this feature.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Sub-pixel displacement commonly refers to finer re-tessellation of geometry that was already tessellated into polygons.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] This re-tessellation results in micropolygons or often microtriangles.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] The vertices of these then get moved along their normals to achieve the displacement mapping.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] True micropolygon renderers have always been able to do what sub-pixel-displacement achieved only recently, but at a higher quality and in arbitrary displacement directions.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Recent developments seem to indicate that some of the renderers that use sub-pixel displacement move towards supporting higher level geometry too.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] As the vendors of these renderers are likely to keep using the term sub-pixel displacement, this will probably lead to more obfuscation of what displacement mapping really stands for, in 3D computer graphics.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] In reference to Microsoft's proprietary High Level Shader Language, displacement mapping can be interpreted as a kind of "vertex-texture mapping" where the values of the texture map do not alter pixel colors (as is much more common), but instead change the position of vertices.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] Unlike bump, normal and parallax mapping, all of which can be said to "fake" the behavior of displacement mapping, in this way a genuinely *rough* surface can be produced from a texture.
[src:terrain-rendering/displacement-mapping] It has to be used in conjunction with adaptive tessellation techniques (that increases the number of rendered polygons according to current viewing settings) to produce highly detailed meshes.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] In computer graphics, a **heightmap** or **heightfield** is a raster image used mainly as Discrete Global Grid in secondary elevation modeling.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Each pixel stores values, such as surface elevation data, for display in 3D computer graphics.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] A heightmap can be used in bump mapping to calculate where this 3D data would create shadow in a material, in displacement mapping to displace the actual geometric position of points over the textured surface, or for terrain where the heightmap is converted into a 3D mesh.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] A heightmap contains one channel interpreted as a distance of displacement or "height" from the "floor" of a surface and sometimes visualized as luma of a grayscale image, with black representing minimum height and white representing maximum height.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] When the map is rendered, the designer can specify the amount of displacement for each unit of the height channel, which corresponds to the “contrast” of the image.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Heightmaps can be stored by themselves in existing grayscale image formats, with or without specialized metadata, or in specialized file formats such as Daylon Leveller, GenesisIV and Terragen documents.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] One may also exploit the use of individual color channels to increase detail.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] For example, a standard RGB 8-bit image can only show 256 values of grey and hence only 256 heights.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] By using colors, a greater number of heights can be stored (for a 24-bit image, 2563 = 16,777,216 heights can be represented (2564 = 4,294,967,296 if the alpha channel is also used)).
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] This technique is especially useful where height varies slightly over a large area.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Using only grey values, because the heights must be mapped to only 256 values, the rendered terrain appears flat, with "steps" in certain places.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Heightmaps are commonly used in geographic information systems, where they are called digital elevation models.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Heightmaps can be created by hand with a classical paint program or a special terrain editor.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] These editors visualize the terrain in 3D and allow the user to modify the surface.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Normally there are tools to raise, lower, smooth or erode the terrain.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Another way to create a terrain is to use a terrain generation algorithm.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] This can be for example a 2D simplex noise function or by diffusion-limited aggregation.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Another method is to reconstruct heightmaps from real world data, for example using synthetic aperture radar.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Heightmaps are widely used in terrain rendering software and modern video games.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Heightmaps are an ideal way to store digital terrain elevations; compared to a regular polygonal mesh, they require substantially less memory for a given level of detail.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Most modern 3D computer modelling programs are capable of using data from heightmaps in the form of bump, normal, or displacement maps to quickly and precisely create complex terrain and other surfaces.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] In the earliest games using software rendering, the elements often represented heights of columns of voxels rendered with ray casting.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] In most newer games, the elements represent the height coordinate of polygons in a mesh.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Although the terms heightmap and heightfield are often indistinguishable from each other, there is still a small difference in the terms.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Heightmap comes from the mathematical term 'map' and heightfield comes from the mathematical term 'vector field'.
[src:terrain-rendering/heightmap] Heightmap is the more correct description because most heightfields are not a (vector) field in mathematical terms but they are always a map (in mathematical terms as well as in the visual representation).
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, **level of detail** (**LOD**) refers to the complexity of a 3D model representation.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD can be decreased as the model moves away from the viewer or according to other metrics such as object importance, viewpoint-relative speed or position.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD techniques increase the efficiency of rendering by decreasing the workload on graphics pipeline stages, usually vertex transformations.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The reduced visual quality of the model is often unnoticed because of the small effect on object appearance when distant or moving fast.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although most of the time LOD is applied to geometry detail only, the basic concept can be generalized.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Recently, LOD techniques also included shader management to keep control of pixel complexity.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A form of level of detail management has been applied to texture maps for years, under the name of mipmapping, also providing higher rendering quality.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] It is commonplace to say that "an object has been *LOD-ed*" when the object is simplified by the underlying *LOD-ing algorithm* as well as a 3D modeler manually creating LOD models.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The origin[1] of all the LOD algorithms for 3D computer graphics can be traced back to an article by James H.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Clark in the October 1976 issue of *Communications of the ACM*.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] At the time, computers were monolithic and rare, and graphics were being driven by researchers.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The hardware itself was completely different, both architecturally and performance-wise.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] As such, many differences could be observed with regard to today's algorithms but also many common points.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The original algorithm presented a much more generic approach to what will be discussed here.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] After introducing some available algorithms for geometry management, it is stated that most fruitful gains came from *"...structuring the environments being rendered"*, allowing to exploit faster transformations and clipping operations.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The proposed algorithm envisions a tree data structure which encodes in its arcs both transformations and transitions to more detailed objects.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In this way, each node encodes an object and according to a fast heuristic, the tree is descended to the leaves which provide each object with more detail.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] When a leaf is reached, other methods could be used when higher detail is needed, such as Catmull's recursive subdivision[2].
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The paper then introduces clipping (not to be confused with culling although often similar), various considerations on the *graphical working set* and its impact on performance, interactions between the proposed algorithm and others to improve rendering speed.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although the algorithm introduced above covers a whole range of level of detail management techniques, real world applications usually employ specialized methods tailored to the information being rendered.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The first method, **discrete level of detail** (**DLOD**), involves creating multiple, discrete versions of the original geometry with decreased levels of geometric detail.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] At runtime, the full-detail models are substituted for the models with reduced detail as necessary.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Due to the discrete nature of the levels, there may be visual popping when one model is exchanged for another.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This may be mitigated by alpha blending or morphing between states during the transition.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The second method, **continuous level of detail** (**CLOD**), uses a structure which contains a continuously variable spectrum of geometric detail.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The structure can then be probed to smoothly choose the appropriate level of detail required for the situation.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A significant advantage of this technique is the ability to locally vary the detail; for instance, the side of a large object nearer to the view may be presented in high detail, while simultaneously reducing the detail on its distant side.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In both cases, LODs are chosen based on some heuristic which is used to judge how much detail is being lost by the reduction in detail, such as by evaluation of the LOD's geometric error relative to the full-detail model.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Objects are then displayed with the minimum amount of detail required to satisfy the heuristic, which is designed to minimize geometric detail as much as possible to maximize performance while maintaining an acceptable level of visual quality.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The basic concept of discrete LOD (DLOD) is to provide various models to represent the same object.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Obtaining those models requires an external algorithm which is often non-trivial and subject of many polygon reduction techniques.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Successive LOD-ing algorithms will simply assume those models are available.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] DLOD algorithms are often used in performance-intensive applications with small data sets which can easily fit in memory.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although out-of-core algorithms could be used, the information granularity is not well suited to this kind of application.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This kind of algorithm is usually easier to get working, providing both faster performance and lower CPU usage because of the few operations involved.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] DLOD methods are often used for "stand-alone" moving objects, possibly including complex animation methods.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A different approach is used for geomipmapping,[3] a popular terrain rendering algorithm because this applies to terrain meshes which are both graphically and topologically different from "object" meshes.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Instead of computing an error and simplify the mesh according to this, geomipmapping takes a fixed reduction method, evaluates the error introduced and computes a distance at which the error is acceptable.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although straightforward, the algorithm provides decent performance.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A discrete LOD approach would cache a certain number of models to be used at different distances.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Because the model can trivially be procedurally generated by its mathematical formulation, using a different number of sample points distributed on the surface is sufficient to generate the various models required.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] To simulate a realistic transform bound scenario, an ad-hoc written application can be used.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The use of simple algorithms and minimum fragment operations ensures that CPU bounding does not occur.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Each frame, the program will compute each sphere's distance and choose a model from a pool according to this information.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] To easily show the concept, the distance at which each model is used is hard coded in the source.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A more involved method would compute adequate models according to the usage distance chosen.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] OpenGL is used for rendering due to its high efficiency in managing small batches, storing each model in a display list thus avoiding communication overheads.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Additional vertex load is given by applying two directional light sources ideally located infinitely far away.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The following table compares the performance of LOD aware rendering and a full detail (*brute force*) method.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Because hardware is geared towards large amounts of detail, rendering low polygon objects may score sub-optimal performances.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] HLOD avoids the problem by grouping different objects together[4].
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This allows for higher efficiency as well as taking advantage of proximity considerations.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD is especially useful in 3D video games.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Video game developers want to provide players with large worlds but are always constrained by hardware, frame rate and the real-time nature of video game graphics.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] With the advent of 3D games in the 1990s, a lot of video games simply did not render distant structures or objects.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Only nearby objects would be rendered and more distant parts would gradually fade, essentially implementing distance fog.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Video games using LOD rendering avoid this fog effect and can render larger areas.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Some notable early examples of LOD rendering in 3D video games include *The Killing Cloud*, *Spyro the Dragon*, *Crash Bandicoot: Warped*, *Unreal Tournament* and *Serious Sam: The First Encounter*.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Most modern 3D games use a combination of LOD rendering techniques, using different models for large structures and distance culling for environment details like grass and trees.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The effect is sometimes still noticeable, for example when the player character flies over the virtual terrain or uses a sniper scope for long distance viewing.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Especially grass and foliage will seem to pop-up when getting closer, also known as foliage culling.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD can also be used to render fractal terrain in real time.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Unreal Engine 5's *Nanite* system essentially implements level-of-detail within meshes instead of just objects as a whole.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD is found in GIS and 3D city models as a similar concept.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] It indicates how thoroughly real-world features have been mapped and how much the model adheres to its real-world counterpart.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Besides the geometric complexity, other metrics such as spatio-semantic coherence, resolution of the texture and attributes can be considered in the LOD of a model.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The standard CityGML contains one of the most prominent LOD categorizations.
[src:terrain-rendering/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The analogy of "LOD-ing" in GIS is referred to as generalization.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The most ancient form of relief depiction in cartography, **hill profiles** are simply illustrations of mountains and hills in profile, placed as appropriate on generally small-scale (broad area of coverage) maps.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] They are seldom used today except as part of an "antique" styling.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Lobeck published *A Physiographic Diagram of the United States*, using an advanced version of the hill profile technique to illustrate the distribution of landforms on a small-scale map.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Erwin Raisz further developed, standardized, and taught this technique, which uses generalized texture to imitate landform shapes over a large area.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] A combination of hill profile and shaded relief, this style of terrain representation is simultaneously idiosyncratic to its creator—often hand-painted—and found insightful in illustrating geomorphological patterns.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] More recently, Tom Patterson developed a computer-generated technique for mapping terrain inspired by Raisz's work, called *plan oblique relief*.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This tool starts with a shaded relief image, then shifts pixels northward proportional to their elevation.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The effect is to make mountains "stand up" and "lay over" features to the north, in the same fashion as hill profiles.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Some viewers are able to see the effect more easily than others.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] There have been multiple attempts to recreate this technique using digital GIS data, with mixed results.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] First developed in France in the 18th Century, **contour lines** (or isohypses) are isolines of equal elevation.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This is the most common way of visualizing elevation quantitatively, and is familiar from topographic maps.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Most 18th- and early 19th-century national surveys did not record relief across the entire area of coverage, calculating only spot elevations at survey points.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] On maps produced by Swisstopo, the color of the contour lines is used to indicate the type of ground: black for bare rock and scree, blue for ice and underwater contours, and brown for earth-covered ground.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The **Tanaka (relief) contours** technique is a method used to illuminate contour lines in order to help visualize terrain.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Lines are highlighted or shaded depending on their relationship to a light source in the Northwest.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] If the object being illustrated would shadow a section of contour line, that contour would be represented with a black band.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Otherwise, slopes facing the light source would be represented by white bands.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This method was developed by Professor Tanaka Kitiro in 1950, but had been experimented with as early as 1870, with little success due to technological limitations in printing.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The resulting terrain at this point was a grayscale image.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Cartographer Berthold Horn later created software to digitally produce Tanaka Contours, and Patrick Kennelly, another cartographer, later found a way to add color to these maps, making them more realistic.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] There are a number of issues with this method.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Historically, printing technology did not reproduce Tanaka contours well, especially the white lines on a gray background.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This method is also very time-consuming.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] In addition, the terraced appearance does not look appealing or accurate in some kinds of terrain.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Shaded relief was traditionally drawn with charcoal, airbrush and other artist's media.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The Swiss cartographer Eduard Imhof is widely regarded as a master of manual hill-shading technique and theory.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Shaded relief is today almost exclusively computer-generated from digital elevation models (DEM).
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The mathematical basis of *analytical hillshading* is to calculate the surface normal at each location, then calculate the angle between that vector and the vector pointing to the illumination using the Dot product; the smaller that angle, the more illumination that location is receiving.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] However, most software implementations use algorithms that shorten those calculations.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This tool is available in a variety of GIS and graphics software, including Photoshop, QGIS, GRASS GIS or ArcMap's Spatial Analyst extension.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Much work has been done in digitally recreating the work of Eduard Imhof, which has been fairly successful in some cases.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] A common criticism of computer-generated analytical hillshading is its stark, artificial look, in which slopes facing the light are solid white, and slopes facing away are solid black.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Raisz called it "plastic shading," and others have said it looks like a moonscape.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] One solution is to incorporate multiple lighting directions to imitate the effect of ambient lighting, creating a much more realistic looking product.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This technique has been found to be most effective for very rugged terrain at medium scales of 1:30,000 to 1:1,000,000.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] It is possible to make the terrain look more realistic by imitating the three-dimensional look of not only the bare land surface, but also the features covering that land surface, such as buildings and plants.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Texture mapping or bump mapping is a technique adapted from Computer graphics that adds a layer of shaded texture to the shaded surface relief that imitates the look of the local land cover.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This technique is most useful at producing realistic maps at relatively large scales, 1:5,000 to 1:50,000.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] One challenge with shaded relief, especially at small scales (1:500,000 or less), is that the technique is very good at visualizing local (high-frequency) relief, but may not effectively show larger features.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] For example, a rugged area of hills and valleys will show as much or more variation than a large, smooth mountain.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Resolution bumping is a hybrid technique developed by NPS cartographer Tom Patterson to mitigate this problem.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] A fine-resolution DEM is averaged with a heavily smoothed version (i.e., significantly coarser resolution).
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] When the hillshading algorithm is applied to this, it has the effect of blending the fine details of the original terrain model with the broader features brought out by the smoothed model.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This technique works best at small scales and in regions that are consistently rugged.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] A three-dimensional view (projected onto a two-dimensional medium) of the surface of the Earth, along with the geographic features resting on it.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Imagined aerial views of cities were first produced during the late Middle Ages, but these "bird's eye views" became very popular in the United States during the 1800s.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The advent of GIS (especially recent advances in 3-D and global visualization) and 3-D graphics modeling software has made the production of realistic aerial views relatively easy, although the execution of quality Cartographic design on these models remains a challenge.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] This is a map in which relief is shown as a three-dimensional object.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The most intuitive way to depict relief is to imitate it at scale.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Hand-crafted dioramas may date back to 200 BCE in China, but mass production did not become available until World War II with the invention of vacuum-formed plastic maps, and computerized machining to create molds efficiently.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Machining is also used to create large custom models from substrates such as high-density foam, and can even color them based on aerial photography by placing an inkjet printhead on the machining device.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The advent of 3D printing has introduced a much more economical means to produce raised-relief maps, although most 3D printers are too small to efficiently produce large dioramas.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] There are two major modes of terrain rendering: top-down and perspective rendering.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Top-down terrain rendering has been known for centuries in the way of cartographic maps.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Perspective terrain rendering has also been known for quite some time.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] However, only with the advent of computers and computer graphics perspective rendering has become mainstream.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] A typical terrain rendering application consists of a terrain database, a central processing unit (CPU), a dedicated graphics processing unit (GPU), and a display.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] A software application is configured to start at initial location in the world space.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The output of the application is screen space representation of the real world on a display.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] There are a number of ways to texture the terrain surface.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Some applications benefit from using artificial textures, such as elevation coloring, checkerboard, or other generic textures.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Some applications attempt to recreate the real-world surface to the best possible representation using aerial photography and satellite imagery.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] In video games, texture splatting is used to texture the terrain surface.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] There are a great variety of methods to generate terrain surfaces.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The main problem solved by all these methods is managing number of processed and rendered polygons.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] It is possible to create a very detailed picture of the world using billions of data points.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] However such applications are limited to static pictures.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Most uses of terrain rendering are moving images, which require the software application to make decisions on how to simplify (by discarding or approximating) source terrain data.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Virtually all terrain rendering applications use level of detail to manage number of data points processed by CPU and GPU.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] There are several modern algorithms for terrain surfaces generating.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Terrain rendering is widely used in computer games to represent both Earth's surface and imaginary worlds.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Some games also have terrain deformation (or deformable terrain).
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] One important application of terrain rendering is in synthetic vision systems.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Pilots flying aircraft benefit greatly from the ability to see terrain surface at all times regardless of conditions outside the aircraft.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Emphasizes hydrological drainage divide and watershed streams.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] Portrayal of relief is especially important in mountainous regions.
[src:terrain-rendering/terrain-rendering] The Commission on Mountain Cartography of the International Cartographic Association is the best-known forum for discussion of theory and techniques for mapping these regions.
